def missing_values(df):
    nan_values_count = df.isna().sum()
    nan_values_percent = nan_values_count / len(df)
    nan_values = pandas.concat([nan_values_count, nan_values_percent], axis=1, keys=['Missing', 'Percent'])
    return nan_values.sort_values(by='Missing', ascending=False)

def plot_unique_count(df, feature):
    counts = df[feature].value_counts()

    counts.plot(kind='bar')
    plt.title('Number of unique values for feature {feature}'.format(feature=feature))
    plt.xlabel('Unique Values')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.show()

def scatter_plot(df, feature1, feature2):    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    sns.scatterplot(data=df, x=feature1, y=feature2)
    plt.title('Scatter plot of {feature1} vs {feature2}'.format(feature1=feature1, feature2=feature2))
    plt.show()

def hexbin_plot(df, feature1, feature2):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    plt.hexbin(df[feature1], df[feature2], gridsize=30, cmap='Blues')
    cb = plt.colorbar(label='count in bin')
    plt.title('Hexbin plot of {feature1} vs {feature2}'.format(feature1=feature1, feature2=feature2))
    plt.show()

def remove_outliers(df, columns, threshold=1.5):
    removed_outliers_num = {}
    new_df = copy.deepcopy(df)
    for col in columns:
        initial_length = len(new_df)
        Q1 = new_df[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = new_df[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        new_df = new_df[~((new_df[col] < (Q1 - threshold * IQR)) | (new_df[col] > (Q3 + threshold * IQR)))]
        final_length = len(new_df)
        removed_outliers_num[col] = initial_length - final_length
    return new_df, removed_outliers_num

def impute_outliers_iqr(df, columns,  threshold=1.5):
    removed_outliers_num = {}
    new_df = copy.deepcopy(df)
    for col in columns:
        Q1 = new_df[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = new_df[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        temp_df = new_df[((new_df[col] < (Q1 - threshold * IQR)) | (new_df[col] > (Q3 + threshold * IQR)))]
        new_df = new_df[~((new_df[col] < (Q1 - threshold * IQR)) | (new_df[col] > (Q3 + threshold * IQR)))]
        median = new_df[col].median()
        num_changes = len(temp_df)
        temp_df[col] = median
        new_df = pandas.concat([new_df,temp_df])
        removed_outliers_num[col] = num_changes
    return new_df, removed_outliers_num

def remove_outliers_z_score(df, columns, threshold=3):
    removed_outliers_num = {}
    new_df = copy.deepcopy(df)
    for col in columns:
        initial_length = len(new_df)
        z_scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(new_df[col]))
        filtered_entries = (z_scores < threshold)
        new_df = new_df[filtered_entries]
        final_length = len(new_df)
        removed_outliers_num[col] = initial_length - final_length
    return new_df, removed_outliers_num

Preprocessing Data¶

7. Missing values¶

We have two primary way in solving missing values problem:

  • Dropping missing values:

    • Dropping Columns: In this method, we will drop the entire column. As a result, we could lose a lot of data, which is generally not appropriate. However, sometimes a column has many missing values and doesn’t provide us with any important information. If we don’t intend to use it, this method can be applied in such cases
    • Dropping Rows: In this method, we would drop and remove any row that has a missing value. However, the problem arises when our missing values are scattered. Each row might have a few missing values, and the same could be true for columns. There might be many rows with one or two missing values that we could fill properly using another method. But if we use this method, we will drop them and lose a lot of important data. This method could be used when a row has many missing values and doesn’t provide any important information.

  • Imputing missing values:

    • Filling with Arbitrary Values:

      • Filling with M This is a simple and straightforward method where missing values are replaced with the mean (average) of the available data. It’s a good representative of the data as a whole. However, it may not always be applicable, especially for columns where the concept of an ‘average’ doesn’t make sense.
      • Filling with Median: When the data has outliers, or extreme values, these can skew the mean. In such cases, it might be more appropriate to use the median (the middle value) for imputation, as it is not affected by outliers and provides a more robust measure of central tendency.
      • Filling with Mode: For categorical data, where data is divided into categories and the concept of mean and median doesn’t apply, the mode (the most frequently occurring value) can be used for imputation. This is particularly useful when dealing with nominal data.
      • Filling with Random Data: This method involves filling missing values with random data, typically within the range of the column’s minimum and maximum values, or among the categories.
      • Filling with Previous or Next Data: In this method, we will replace missing values with either the previous or the next value. This method is particularly useful for data where there is a time dependency.

    • Predicting missing values: Another method is to predict the missing values based on other observable features.

9. Nomalizing and Standardizing¶

Standardizing and normalizing values for data in machine learning are important techniques that can help to improve the performance and accuracy of various models. They involve transforming the data to make it more suitable for modeling, by reducing the impact of outliers, scaling the features to a common range, and ensuring that the data is on the same scale.

  • Standardization is useful when you want to ensure zero mean and unit standard deviation for your features. This can help to make your data more comparable and reduce the effect of outliers. Standardization is also helpful when your data follows a Gaussian (bell curve) distribution or when you are using algorithms that are sensitive to the scale of the features, such as gradient descent based algorithms.
  • Normalization is useful when you want to scale your features to a range between 0 and 1 or -1 and 1. This can help to make your data more suitable for algorithms that do not assume a specific distribution, such as k-nearest neighbors and artificial neural networks. Normalization is also helpful when you have features that have different scales or units of measurement.
In [ ]:
def normalize_dataframe(df, exceptions=[]):
    min_max_scaler = preprocessing.MinMaxScaler()
    for col in df.columns:
        if col not in exceptions:
            df[col] = min_max_scaler.fit_transform(df[[col]])
    return df

def standardize_dataframe(df, exceptions=[]):
    scaler = preprocessing.StandardScaler()
    for col in df.columns:
        if col not in exceptions:
            df[col] = scaler.fit_transform(df[[col]])
    return df

10. Categorical Variables¶

  • Label encoding: Assigns a unique integer value to each category. It’s simple and easy to implement, but it doesn’t preserve the order or hierarchy of the categories and may introduce sparsity or multicollinearity issues.

  • One-hot encoding: Creates a binary vector for each category, where only one element is 1 and the rest are 0. It preserves the order and hierarchy of the categories, but it increases the dimensionality of the data significantly.

  • Ordinal encoding: Assigns a numerical value to each category based on its rank or order. It captures the meaningful relationship between categories that have an inherent order or ranking.

  • Binary encoding: Combines label encoding and one-hot encoding by converting each integer value into a binary number and creating binary features for each bit in the binary representation. It reduces the dimensionality of the data compared to one-hot encoding.

  • Frequency encoding: Replaces each category with its frequency or count in the dataset. It’s useful when there are many categories in the dataset but they are not very different from each other in terms of their distribution or importance.

In [ ]:
def one_hot_encode(df, column):
    return pandas.get_dummies(df, columns=[column])

def label_encode(df, column):
    le = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
    dataframe = copy.deepcopy(df)
    dataframe[column] = le.fit_transform(dataframe[column])
    return dataframe

def ordinal_encode(df, column):
    oe = preprocessing.OrdinalEncoder()
    dataframe = copy.deepcopy(df)
    dataframe[column] = oe.fit_transform(dataframe[[column]])
    return dataframe

def binary_encode(df, column):
    be = ce.BinaryEncoder(cols=[column])
    return be.fit_transform(df)

def frequency_encode(df, column):
    fe = df.groupby(column).size()/len(df)
    dataframe = copy.deepcopy(df)
    dataframe.loc[:, column + "_freq_encode"] = dataframe[column].map(fe)
    return df

12. Train and Test¶

The ratio of the division between the training and test sets in machine learning depends on various factors, such as the size of the dataset, the complexity of the model, and the desired level of accuracy. There is no definitive rule for choosing the optimal ratio, but some common values are 80:20, 75:25, and 70:30.

There are different methods for dividing and creating these two categories of data. One method is to use a random split, where each data point has an equal chance of being assigned to either the training or test set. This method is simple and fast, but it may not be representative of the true distribution of the data. Another method is to use a stratified split, where each class or category of data has a fixed proportion in both sets. This method ensures that the training and test sets have similar characteristics and do not introduce bias in the model evaluation. A third method is to use a cross-validation technique, where multiple subsets of data are used to train and test different models. This method allows for more accurate estimation of the model performance and reduces overfitting.

In [ ]:
def random_split(X_df, Y_df, test_size=0.2, random_state=42):
    X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test= train_test_split(X_df, Y_df, test_size=test_size, random_state=random_state)
    return  X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test

def stratified_split(df, target, test_size=0.2, random_state=42):
    sss = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=1, test_size=test_size, random_state=random_state)
    for train_index, test_index in sss.split(df, df[target]):
        train_df, test_df = df.iloc[train_index], df.iloc[test_index]
    return train_df, test_df

13. Validation¶

In some cases, a third category of data, known as validation data, is utilized. In this scenario, the primary dataset is partitioned into three sections: training, validation, and testing. These sections typically comprise approximately 70%, 15%, and 15% of the data, respectively.

The validation data serves as a preliminary testing ground for the trained model prior to the application of the testing data. This stage facilitates the fine-tuning of the classifier’s hyperparameters.

14. K-fold Cross Validation¶

Linear Regression¶

Main form of simple linear regression function: $$f(x) = \alpha x + \beta$$

here we want to find the bias ($\alpha$) and slope($\beta$) by minimizing the derivation of the Residual Sum of Squares (RSS) function:

  • step 1: Compute RSS of the training data

$$ RSS = \Sigma (y_i - (\hat{\beta} + \hat{\alpha} * x_i) )^2 $$

  • step 2: Compute the derivatives of the RSS function in terms of $\alpha$ and $\beta$, and set them equal to 0 to find the desired parameters

$$ \frac{\partial RSS}{\partial \beta} = \Sigma (-f(x_i) + \hat{\beta} + \hat{\alpha} * x_i) = 0$$ $$ \to \beta = \hat{y} - \hat{\alpha} \hat{x} \to (1)$$

$$ \frac{\partial RSS}{\partial \alpha} = \Sigma (-2 x_i y_i + 2 \hat{\beta} x_i + 2\hat{\alpha} x_i ^ 2) = 0 \to (2)$$

$$ (1) , (2) \to \hat{\alpha} = \frac{\Sigma{(x_i - \hat{x})(y_i - \hat{y})}}{\Sigma{(x_i - \hat{x})^2}} $$ $$ \hat{\beta} = y - \hat{a} x$$

Based on the above formula, implement the function below to compute the parameters of a simple linear regression

In [ ]:
def simple_linear_regression(input_feature, output):
    mean_x = sum(input_feature) / len(input_feature)
    mean_y = sum(output) / len(output)

    numerator = sum([xi*yi for xi,yi in zip(input_feature, output)]) - len(input_feature)*mean_x*mean_y
    denominator = sum([xi**2 for xi in input_feature]) - len(input_feature)*mean_x**2

    slope = numerator / denominator
    bias = mean_y - (slope*mean_x)

    return bias, slope

Now that we have a model and can make predictions, let's evaluate our model using Root Mean Square Error (RMSE). RMSE is the square root of the mean of the squared differences between the residuals, and the residuals is just a fancy word for the difference between the predicted output and the true output.

Complete the following function to compute the RSME of a simple linear regression model given the input_feature, output, intercept and slope:

In [ ]:
def get_root_mean_square_error(predicted_values, outputs):
    squared_diffs = [(predicted - actual)**2 for predicted, actual in zip(predicted_values, outputs)]
    mean_squared_diff = sum(squared_diffs) / len(squared_diffs)
    rmse = mean_squared_diff**0.5
    return rmse

The RMSE has no bound, thus it becomes challenging to determine whether a particular RMSE value is considered good or bad without any reference point. Instead, we use R2 score. The R2 score is calculated by comparing the sum of the squared differences between the actual and predicted values of the dependent variable to the total sum of squared differences between the actual and mean values of the dependent variable. The R2 score is formulated as below:

$$R^2 = 1 - \frac{SSres}{SStot} = 1 - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_{i,true} - y_{i,pred})^2}{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_{i,true} - \bar{y}_{true})^2} $$

Complete the following function to calculate the R2 score of a given input_feature, output, bias, and slope:

In [ ]:
def get_r2_score(predicted_values, outputs):
    mean_outputs = outputs.mean()
    SS_tot = sum([(output - mean_outputs)**2 for output in outputs])
    SS_res = sum([(output - predicted)**2 for output, predicted in zip(outputs, predicted_values)])
    r2_score = 1 - (SS_res / SS_tot)
    return r2_score
15.¶

As stated in the description, we are approximating the best linear line that we can apply to the data. The best line is the one that has the least error. We first consider a function for its error and say that this function is equal to its minimum value at a point where its derivative is zero. Therefore, we take the derivative of it and set it equal to zero. According to this assumption, by taking the derivative with respect to two variables, we can obtain two equations. Since we also have two unknown variables, we can find the variables with the help of the equations.

17. RSS, MSE, RMSE, R2 Score¶
  • Residual Sum of Squares (RSS): RSS is the sum of the squared differences between the observed and predicted values. It provides a raw measure of the total errors made by our model. However, it doesn’t provide an average error rate and its value increases with the number of data points.

$$\text{RSS} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2$$

  • Mean Squared Error (MSE): MSE is the average of the squared differences between the observed and predicted values. It provides an average error rate and is more sensitive to larger errors due to squaring. But, it’s not in the same unit as the original output.

$$\text{MSE} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2$$

  • Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): RMSE is the square root of MSE. It provides an average error rate in the same unit as the original output. It’s also more sensitive to larger errors due to squaring in MSE.

$$\text{RMSE} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2}$$

  • R2 Score: R2 Score, also known as the coefficient of determination, measures the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable(s). It provides a measure of how well unseen samples are likely to be predicted by the model. The best possible score is 1.0 and it can be negative (because the model can be arbitrarily worse).

$$\text{R}^2 = 1 - \frac{\text{RSS}}{\text{TSS}}$$

Where:

$$\text{TSS} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \bar{y})^2$$

Multiple Regression¶

Multiple regression is a statistical technique that aims to model the relationship between a dependent variable and two or more independent variables.

Multiple regression with n independent variables is expressed as follows:

$$f(x) = \beta _{0} + \beta_{1} x_{1} + \beta_{2} x_{2} + \beta_{3} x_{3} + \beta_{4} x_{4} + ... + \beta_{n} x_{n} + c $$

To optimize the model for accurate predictions, multiple regression commonly employs iterative algorithms such as gradient descent.

The main goal of the optimization process is to make our predictions as close as possible to the actual values. We measure the prediction error using a cost function, usually denoted as $J(\beta)$.

$$ J(\beta)= \frac {1}{2m} Σ_{i=0}^{m-1}(y_i - (\hat \beta _{0} + \hat \beta_{1} x_{1} + \hat \beta_{2} x_{2} + \hat \beta_{3} x_{3} + \hat \beta_{4} x_{4} + ... + \hat \beta_{n} x_{n}) )^2 $$

Gradient descent iteratively adjusts the coefficients $(\beta_i)$ to minimize the cost function. The update rule for each coefficient is:

$$\beta_{i} = \beta _ {i} - \alpha \frac {∂J(\beta)}{∂\beta_{i}}$$

$$ \frac {∂J(\beta)}{∂\beta_{i}} = \frac {1}{m}Σ_{j=0}^{m-1}(y_j - (\hat \beta _{0} + \hat \beta_{1} x_{j1} + \hat \beta_{2} x_{j2} + \hat \beta_{3} x_{j3} + \hat \beta_{4} x_{j4} + ... + \hat \beta_{n} x_{jn})) x_{ji} $$

Predicting output given regression weights¶

Based on the formula above and np.dot() method, complete this function to compute the predictions for an entire matrix of features given the matrix, bias, and the weights. Provide an explanation of np.dot method and the reasoning behind using this method in your code:

In [ ]:
def predict_output(feature_matrix, weights, bias):
    predict_output = np.dot(feature_matrix,weights)
    predict_output += bias
    return predict_output

Computing the Derivative¶

As we saw, the cost function is the sum over the data points of the squared difference between an observed output and a predicted output.

Since the derivative of a sum is the sum of the derivatives, we can compute the derivative for a single data point and then sum over data points. We can write the squared difference between the observed output and predicted output for a single point as follows:

$$ (output - (const* w _{0} + [feature_1] * w_{1} + ...+ [feature_n] * w_{n} ))^2 $$

With n feautures and a const , So the derivative will be :

$$ 2 * (output - (const* w _{0} + [feature_1] * w_{1} + ...+ [feature_n] * w_{n} )) $$

The term inside the paranethesis is just the error (difference between prediction and output). So we can re-write this as:

$$2 * error*[feature_i] $$

That is, the derivative for the weight for feature i is the sum (over data points) of 2 times the product of the error and the feature itself. In the case of the constant then this is just twice the sum of the errors!

Recall that twice the sum of the product of two vectors is just twice the dot product of the two vectors. Therefore the derivative for the weight for feature_i is just two times the dot product between the values of feature_i and the current errors.

With this in mind, complete the following derivative function which computes the derivative of the weight given the value of the feature (over all data points) and the errors (over all data points).

In [ ]:
def feature_derivative(errors, feature):
    derivative = 2 * np.dot(errors, feature)
    return derivative

Gradient Descent¶

Now we will write a function that performs a gradient descent. The basic premise is simple. Given a starting point we update the current weights by moving in the negative gradient direction. Recall that the gradient is the direction of increase and therefore the negative gradient is the direction of decrease and we're trying to minimize a cost function.

The amount by which we move in the negative gradient direction is called the 'step size'. We stop when we are 'sufficiently close' to the optimum. We define this by requiring that the magnitude (length) of the gradient vector to be smaller than a fixed 'tolerance'.

With this in mind, complete the following gradient descent function below using your derivative function above. For each step in the gradient descent we update the weight for each feature befofe computing our stopping criteria.

In [ ]:
def regression_gradient_descent(feature_matrix, outputs, initial_weights, bias, step_size, tolerance):
    m_gradiant = np.inf
    weights = np.array(initial_weights)
    while m_gradiant > tolerance:
        predictions = predict_output(feature_matrix, weights, bias)
        errors = predictions - outputs
        square_sum_gradiant = 0
        for i in range(len(weights)):
            derivate = feature_derivative(errors,feature_matrix[:,i])
            weights[i] -= step_size*derivate
            square_sum_gradiant += derivate**2
            
        
        derivate = feature_derivative(errors, np.ones(len(errors)))
        bias -= step_size*derivate
        m_gradiant = np.sqrt(square_sum_gradiant)
        
    return weights, bias

# Utility functions for multiple regression

def normalize_features(chosen_features, data_frame):
    df = copy.deepcopy(data_frame)
    for feature in chosen_features:
        df[feature] = (df[feature] - df[feature].mean()) / df[feature].std()
    return df


def n_feature_regression(chosen_feature_matrix, target_matrix, keywords):
    initial_weights = keywords['initial_weights']
    step_size = keywords['step_size']
    tolerance = keywords['tolerance']
    bias = keywords['bias']

    weights, bias = regression_gradient_descent(chosen_feature_matrix, target_matrix, initial_weights, bias, step_size,
                                                tolerance)

    return weights, bias

class DTreeClassifier:
    def __init__(self, X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test):
        self.X_train = X_train
        self.Y_train = Y_train
        self.X_test = X_test
        self.Y_test = Y_test
        self.dtreeclr = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy', max_depth=8, min_samples_split=8,
                            min_samples_leaf=2, random_state=1)
        self.dtreeclr.fit(self.X_train, self.Y_train)   
        self.prediction = self.dtreeclr.predict(self.X_test)   
    
    def accuracy(self):
        return metrics.accuracy_score(self.Y_test, self.prediction)
    
    def train_accuracy(self):
        predict_train = self.dtreeclr.predict(self.X_train)
        return metrics.accuracy_score(self.Y_train, predict_train)
    
    def plot_confusion_matrix(self):
        matrix_dtree = metrics.confusion_matrix(self.Y_test, self.prediction)
        matrix_disp = metrics.ConfusionMatrixDisplay(matrix_dtree)
        matrix_disp.plot(cmap='Blues')
        plt.title('DecisionTreeClassfier Confusion Matrix')
        plt.show()
    
    def plot_decision_tree(self):
        plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
        plt.title("Decision Tree Classifier")
        plt.xlabel("Features")
        plt.ylabel("Classes")
        plot_tree(self.dtreeclr, feature_names = list(self.X_train.columns))
        plt.show()
    
    def grid_search_cv(self):
        param_grid = { 'criterion' : ['entropy'],
                      'max_depth' : range(4,12),
                     'min_samples_split': range(2,12),
                     'min_samples_leaf' : range(1,10),
                     'random_state': [1]}
        grid = GridSearchCV(self.dtreeclr, param_grid, cv = 10, scoring = 'accuracy')
        grid.fit(self.X_train, self.Y_train)
        print('\nBest Score: ',grid.best_score_)
        print('Best Params: ', grid.best_params_)
        
        y_pred = grid.predict(self.X_test)
        print('Accuracy: ', metrics.accuracy_score(self.Y_test, y_pred))
        return grid.best_params_

21. Overfitting and Underfitting¶

Before we delve into the explanations of underfitting and overfitting, it’s essential to familiarize ourselves with the concepts of bias and variance.

  • Bias is the difference between the model’s predicted value and the actual value. It is caused by wrong assumptions or simplifications in the model. For example, if a model assumes that the data is linear when it is actually non-linear, it will have a high bias. A high bias means that the model cannot capture the complexity or variability of the data, and it will perform poorly on both the training and testing data. This is called underfitting.
  • Variance is the sensitivity of the model to changes in the training data. It is caused by noise or randomness in the data. For example, if a model has many parameters or features, it will be more prone to overfitting. Overfitting means that the model learns too much from the training data and memorizes it, but it cannot generalize well to new or unseen data. This is called overfitting

And now about overfitting and underfitting:

  • Overfitting occurs when a model is too complex or has too many parameters, and it learns the noise or random fluctuations in the training data instead of the underlying pattern. This makes the model perform well on the training data, but poorly on new or unseen data. Overfitting can be reduced by using techniques such as cross-validation, regularization, early stopping, or ensembling
  • Underfitting occurs when a model is too simple or has too few parameters, and it cannot capture the complexity or variability of the data. This makes the model perform poorly on both the training and testing data. Underfitting can be reduced by using techniques such as increasing model complexity, increasing number of features, scaling features, or using more training data

class RandomForestModel:
    def __init__(self, X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test, n_estimators=100, max_depth=8):
        self.X_train = X_train
        self.Y_train = Y_train
        self.X_test = X_test
        self.Y_test = Y_test
        self.n_estimators = n_estimators
        self.max_depth = max_depth
        self.model = RandomForestClassifier(criterion='entropy',
                                            max_depth=self.max_depth,
                                            n_estimators=self.n_estimators,
                                            random_state=1)
        self.train()
        self.y_pred = self.predict(self.X_test)
        
    def train(self):
        self.model.fit(self.X_train, self.Y_train)

    def predict(self, data):
        return self.model.predict(data)

    def plot_confusion_matrix(self):
        matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(self.Y_test, self.y_pred)
        matrix_disp = metrics.ConfusionMatrixDisplay(matrix)
        matrix_disp.plot(cmap='Blues')
        plt.title('Random Forest Confusion Matrix')
        plt.show()
    
    def accuracy(self):
        return metrics.accuracy_score(self.Y_test, self.y_pred)
    
    def grid_search_cv(self):
        search_params = {
            'n_estimators': range(70, 230, 30),
            'criterion': ['entropy'],
            'max_depth': range(4, 10),
            'random_state': [1]
        }
        grid = GridSearchCV(self.model, search_params, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=2)
        grid.fit(self.X_train, self.Y_train)
        print('\nBest Score: ',grid.best_score_)
        print('Best Params: ', grid.best_params_)
        pred = grid.predict(self.X_test)
        print('Accuracy: ', metrics.accuracy_score(self.Y_test, pred))

24. Random Forest Hyperparamteres¶

In terms of RandomForestClassifier, we have these hyperparameters:

  • n_estimators: The number of trees in the forest.
  • max_depth: The maximum depth of each tree.
  • min_samples_split: The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node.
  • min_samples_leaf: The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node.
  • max_features: The number of features to consider when looking for the best split at each node.

We can choose two of them to compare their effects on the model.

25. Bias and Variance¶

Bias

Bias refers to the discrepancy between the average prediction of our model and the actual value we aim to predict. High bias can lead an algorithm to overlook the pertinent relationships between features and target outputs, resulting in underfitting.

Variance

Variance represents the fluctuation in model prediction for a specific data point, or a value that signifies the dispersion of the data. High variance can lead to overfitting, where the model captures the random noise in the training data instead of the intended outputs.

Random Forests vs Decision Trees

Random Forests are an ensemble method that amalgamates multiple decision trees to diminish variance and enhance generalization. On the other hand, Decision Trees exhibit higher variance and lower bias as they are prone to overfitting with training data.

Differential Privacy¶

26.¶

Adding noise to a dataset is a way to hide personal details and improve safety. It makes it harder to find out who’s who in the dataset, reducing the chance of someone being identified. However, it might make the data less useful. The effect of adding noise depends on what the data is used for. If we add noise in a certain way (called differential privacy), it can give a strong promise of privacy protection. It’s important to find a balance between keeping privacy and keeping the data useful. Using methods like differential privacy can give strong promises of keeping individual’s information private.

27. Laplace noise and Exponential noise¶

Laplace noise and exponential noise are two types of noise that can be used to add privacy to data. They are both based on the Laplace distribution, which is a continuous probability distribution that has fatter tails than the normal distribution. The Laplace distribution can be thought of as two exponential distributions (with an additional location parameter) spliced together along the abscissa.

Laplace noise is a special case of Laplace distribution where the scale parameter b is equal to 1. This means that the Laplace noise has zero mean and constant variance. Laplace noise can be used to add privacy to any function f: N|X| → Rk, where N|X| denotes the set of all non-negative real numbers. The Laplace mechanism adds i.i.d. random variables from Lap(Δf/ϵ) to f(x), where Δf is the sensitivity of f, ϵ is a small positive constant, and i.i.d. means independent and identically distributed.

Exponential noise is another special case of Laplace distribution where b is equal to 1. However, exponential noise has a different shape than Laplace noise, as it has a steeper peak and thinner tails. Exponential noise can also be used to add privacy to any function f: N|X| → Rk, but it has some advantages over Laplace noise in certain situations. For example, exponential noise can be more robust against outliers and extreme values than Laplace noise. Exponential noise can also be more suitable for adding privacy to functions that have different scales or ranges than others.

The main difference between Laplace noise and exponential noise is their shape and properties. Both are based on the same underlying distribution, but they have different characteristics that affect their performance in differential privacy applications. Depending on the context and the goal, one may choose either one or both types of noise to add privacy to data.

Gradient Boosting¶

29.¶

Gradient boosting is a machine learning strategy that enhances predictive accuracy by integrating predictions from multiple models. It’s especially beneficial for tackling regression and classification problems. The fundamental concept of gradient boosting involves initiating with a basic learner, like a decision tree, and progressively incorporating more models to rectify the preceding ones’ errors. The new model aims to reduce the prediction error by modifying its weights based on the loss function’s gradient. The gradient signifies the loss function’s steepest descent direction, so incorporating more models escalates the complexity and diminishes the model’s bias.

Gradient boosting has several variants, including XGBoost, LightGBM, and CatBoost. These variants employ distinct optimization algorithms and regularization techniques to expedite the training process and avert overfitting. Furthermore, gradient boosting can be amalgamated with other techniques, such as feature selection, dimensionality reduction, or ensemble learning, to boost its performance.

30.¶

XGBoost is a popular machine learning library that implements gradient boosting algorithms for decision trees. Gradient boosting is a technique that combines multiple weak models (such as shallow decision trees) into a strong model by iteratively adding new models that correct the errors of the previous ones. XGBoost is designed to be fast, scalable, and accurate for various types of problems, such as regression, classification, and ranking.

A decision tree is a simple model that splits the input data into branches based on some criteria. Each branch represents a possible outcome or prediction. The final prediction is made by choosing the leaf node (the end of a branch) that has the highest probability or value. A decision tree can be visualized as a graph, where each node is a feature or variable, each edge is a split condition, and each leaf node is an outcome or prediction.

XGBoost uses different methods to build and update decision trees, such as exact, approximate, and histogram methods. Each method has its own advantages and disadvantages in terms of speed, accuracy, and complexity. XGBoost also supports various features and parameters to customize the behavior of the algorithm, such as regularization, learning rate, subsampling, pruning, etc.

import xgboost as xgb


class XGBoostClassifier:
    def __init__(self, X_train, Y_train, X_test, Y_test):
        self.X_train = X_train
        self.Y_train = Y_train
        self.X_test = X_test
        self.Y_test = Y_test
        self.xgb = xgb.XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False, eval_metric='mlogloss')
        self.xgb.fit(self.X_train, self.Y_train)
        self.prediction = self.xgb.predict(self.X_test)

    def accuracy(self):
        return metrics.accuracy_score(self.Y_test, self.prediction)

    def train_accuracy(self):
        predict_train = self.xgb.predict(self.X_train)
        return metrics.accuracy_score(self.Y_train, predict_train)

    def plot_confusion_matrix(self):
        matrix_xgb = metrics.confusion_matrix(self.Y_test, self.prediction)
        matrix_disp = metrics.ConfusionMatrixDisplay(matrix_xgb)
        matrix_disp.plot(cmap='Blues')
        plt.title('XGBoostClassifier Confusion Matrix')
        plt.show()
        
    def grid_search_cv(self):
        param_grid = {
            'max_depth': [3, 4, 5],
            'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.01, 0.05],
            'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
            'gamma': [0, 0.5, 1],
            'colsample_bytree': [0.3, 0.5, 0.7],
        }
        grid = GridSearchCV(self.xgb, param_grid, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=2)
        grid.fit(self.X_train, self.Y_train)
        print('\nBest Score: ',grid.best_score_)
        print('Best Params: ', grid.best_params_)
        pred = grid.predict(self.X_test)
        print('Accuracy: ', metrics.accuracy_score(self.Y_test, pred))
        return grid.best_params_
